{
  "doc_id": "47118",
  "text": "Nonalcoholic fatty liver disease (NAFLD) is defined as the pathological accumulation of lipids in hepatocytes without significant alcohol consumption, use of steatogenic medication or hereditary disorders [CITATION_1] . The pathologic classification of NAFLD encompasses isolated hepatic steatosis, nonalcoholic steatohepatitis (NASH) and cryptogenic fibrosis/cirrhosis [CITATION_2] . As the global obesity epidemic grows, the incidence of NAFLD is increasing; in morbidly obese adults, the prevalence of NAFLD is more than 90% [CITATION_3] , and the prevalence is thought to reach up to 50% in obese children [CITATION_4] . Unfortunately, patients with NAFLD show increased rates of overall mortality compared to matched control populations [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . Although much progress has been made towards gaining a better understanding of the pathogenesis of NAFLD, the exact molecular mechanisms remain unclear.",
